<TEXT>
fires tore through brush and trees across the west on sunday 
with one threatening an old cavalry fort where sioux chief crazy 
horse was killed but lower temperatures and higher humidity were 
helping firefighters 
fires burned out of control in arizona new mexico colorado 
nebraska utah california oregon and wyoming a fire in montana 
was contained light rain and lower temperatures all but 
extinguished three large wildfires in interior alaska including one 
that charred 24000 acres 
the federal boise interagency fire center in idaho said about 
31000 fires had been reported through sunday and about 15 million 
acres have burned this year according to information officer milt 
williams by the same time last year 55000 fires had been reported 
and 765000 acres blackened 
the center was coordinating the efforts of 10000 firefighters 
he said it also had 50 air tankers in use up from 42 on saturday 
were having some storm activity bringing some relief in the 
southwest but when it moves east its creating more fires due to 
lightning in eastern utah and colorado williams said 
the biggest fire in the west was the diamond creek fire at 
12500 acres in eastern utah but it was 80 percent contained by 
sunday morning said mary plumb a spokeswoman for the bureau of 
land managements moab district efforts were focused on keeping it 
out of a 50000acre state roadless area similar to a federal 
wilderness zone she said 
its real wild rugged country real heavy timber plumb 
said we dont want it to get in there 
several other fires in the state were nearing containment by fire 
lines officials said 
a lightningsparked fire burned along a 20mile front in 
northwestern nebraska threatening the community of crawford and 
forcing the evacuation of more than 629 people from a hospital 
nursing home and fort robinson state park 
nebraska gov kay orr issued an emergency declaration making 
state money available and ordered national guard troops to help 
fight the fire 
the blaze was within a halfmile of the old fort robinson where 
crazy horse was killed by guards in 1877 and fire burned to within 
1 miles of crawford a city of 1300 authorities said 
the 6milewide blaze scorched 50000 to 100000 acres said 
deputy state fire marshal jerry larson 
we could see whole lines of trees exploding said marc 
anthony a state game and parks commissioner who flew over the fire 
a mushroom cloud of smoke was visible about 90 miles away 
the fire burned 10000 to 12000 acres of trees scrub and 
grassland in the 22000acre parks rugged canyons estimated park 
superintendent vince rotherham it also charred part of a wildlife 
refuge and private land 
temperatures around 90 degrees and variable wind complicated 
firefighting efforts officials said 
but higher humidity and less wind sunday helped firefighters get 
the upper hand on the 10025acre divide fire in the gila national 
forest in southwestern new mexico us forest service spokesman jim 
ness said conditions sunday were favorable to containing the blaze 
started by lightning june 30 
higher humidity lower temperatures and less wind in arizona also 
helped crews fighting fires that had burned more than 40000 acres 
of forest range and brush and most were more than 50 percent 
contained thunderstorms were reported overnight 
a 1000acre fire in the grand canyon briefly threatened 
president theodore roosevelts hunting cabin said spokeswoman 
barbara tracey 
in northeastern california a windfanned fire had destroyed 
3500 acres of remote brush land and seven buildings by sunday and 
firefighters constructed a firebreak as wide as an eightlane 
highway across its southern path a separate 2800acre brush blaze 
blamed on arson threatened the ventana wilderness in big sur 
between 30 and 50 families evacuated saturday night from two 
sparsely populated areas in the 3500acre fires path were allowed 
to return to their homes sunday officials said the fire on the 
eastern slopes of the sierra nevada had destroyed three homes a 
garage three barns and numerous sheds and other small structures 
officials said 
the butte fire five miles east of oroville north of sacramento 
was brought under control sunday morning after destroying four homes 
and six outbuildings said dj stephens a state forestry 
department spokeswoman 
a brush fire burned 2000 acres in the laguna mountains about 40 
miles east of san diego sweeping through a campground and the 
cuyapaipe indian reservation people were asked to evacuate the 
campground and firefighters protected buildings on the reservation 
in colorado a 100acre fire destroyed at least five homes and 
forced the evacuation of five subdivisions near sugarloaf mountain 
about 25 miles northwest of denver officials said 
archaeologists from around the southwest were called to help 
firefighters at mesa verde national park in southwestern colorado 
protect ancient indian relics from a 700acre blaze numerous 
lightningstarted fires were reported elsewhere around the state 
anns fire in the bridgerteton national forest of western 
wyoming slowed over the weekend thanks partly to cooler weather 
fire officials say it was about 60 percent contained sunday after 
having burned at least 3477 acres in five days according to forest 
spokesman ed christian 
