<TEXT>
two strong earthquakes hit southwest of tokyo within 
a minute of each other sunday triggering landslides and injuring at 
least 18 people police said they were among thousands of tremors 
that have rocked the area in 10 days 
the first quake registering 55 on the richter scale occurred 
at 1109 am the central meteorological agency said the second 
was slightly weaker but its precise magnitude was not immediately 
known 
the first quake was centered in the pacific ocean near atami on 
the izu peninsula about 60 miles southwest of tokyo officials said 
it was the strongest among at least 19363 tremors 433 of them 
strong enough to be felt by residents that have shaken the izu 
peninsula since june 30 the agency said 
landslides occurred at 16 places and roads were cracked in 10 
places in ito on the izu peninsula said a police official of 
shizuoka prefecture or state 
some of the injuries all blamed on the larger quake occurred 
when furniture fell on people in their homes police said two 
people were burned from spattering oil in a kitchen said the police 
official on condition of anonymity 
the official said 2600 households lost electricity for four 
hours masayoshi abe a railway official said the regions 
highspeed commuter trains were stopped for up to 61 minutes 
delaying about 20000 people 
the agency gave no reason for the increased seismic activity 
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an 
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a 
seismograph every increase of one number means that the ground 
motion is 10 times greater 
a quake of magnitude 5 can cause considerable damage in populated 
areas while one measuring 6 can cause severe damage 
