<TEXT>
the explosion of a major pipeline in the ural 
mountains decreased the countrys gas supply by 20 percent forcing 
cuts in gas exports and supplies to domestic factories and 
consumers a government official said 
gas minister viktor s chernomyrdin also said soviet consumers 
should conserve gas used in kitchen stoves and brace for shortages 
of rubber and plastic goods made from the petroleum products the 
pipeline carried 
a 1153mile pipeline carrying a mixture of benzine propane and 
butane from western siberia to chemical factories and kitchen stoves 
in the countrys center burst june 4 as two passenger trains were 
passing 
a spark from the transsiberian railroad trains touched off an 
explosion and fire incinerating more than 600 passengers 745 miles 
southeast of moscow 
president mikhail s gorbachev said workers noticed a drop in 
pressure caused by the leak but increased the flow instead of 
shutting the line down 
on the day of the accident a gas ministry spokesman told the 
associated press the gas flow from the region was quickly diverted 
to an alternate pipeline and that no significant disruption 
occurred it was not immediately possible to explain the discrepency 
in the two officials assessments 
chernomyrdin told the government daily izvestia in an interview 
published saturday that the pipeline carried 13500 tons of the 
17000 tons of liquefied gas that western siberia supplies daily to 
the countrys center he said the accident caused a daily production 
shortfall of 5000 tons 
izvestia did not say how many tons of gas the nation produces 
but it said the accident caused a 20 percent reduction in gas 
supplies in june 
chernomyrdin said many petrochemical factories are either idle or 
working at half strength because of the gas shortfall he also said 
raw petroleum products supplied to industry will be cut by 25 
percent in the third quarter of the year causing losses in the 
millions of rubles 
the gas shortage and decreased plastic and rubber supplies will 
affect soviet consumers already grappling with shortages of meat 
butter toothpaste sugar and matches chernomyrdin said gas 
supplies to the 41 million stoves in the soviet union will be cut 6 
percent in the third quarter 
the minister urged people to conserve gas in their homes and use 
alternate fuels in country houses 
the disruption also is hurting the nations attempts to obtain 
foreign currency badly needed in gorbachevs drive to modernize 
domestic industry 
the soviet union is the worlds largest oil and gas producer 
chernomyrdin said the loss of the pipeline would force a 60 
percent reduction in gas exports in the third quarter depriving the 
country of 125 million in foreign currency income 
because it wont be able to fulfill some contracts with foreign 
customers the soviets will have to pay 16 million in fines and 
spend 312 million in foreign currency on repair equipment in all 
he said repairs will take half a year and cost more than 156 
million 
natural and manmade disasters have hampered the gorbachev 
administration 
the nation spent millions to clean up and rebuild after the 1986 
chernobyl nuclear power plant accident and the december 1988 
earthquake in armenia 
</TEXT>
